				I think the best way to solve the marriage issue is to remove any ties between marriage and the government entirely.  Right now, people get certain benefits or hindrances from their marital status through taxes and similar government regulated things.  Why should the government treat two people who are committed and/or in love differently?  It's like saying dog owners should get tax breaks and cat owners shouldn't.<br /><br />By not letting the government have any involvement with marriage, it won't MATTER if anyone likes it or doesn't like it.  They'll have to let it happen anyway.  Of course, I'm not talking about things like marrying minors or family pets or anything.. somethings still need to be protected, like those examples.  I think this is the Libertarian position on this issue as well.<br /><br />And a word about the Bible Thumping Legislators... if the reason for barring Gay Marriage is that it's religiously wrong, then how can you decide to make laws against it?  Laws born of religion are the mark of a theocracy and the opposite of "separation of church and state".  I'm not sure that this is any lawmakers "official position" on the reason for Gay Marriage to be banned, but religion really shouldn't have anything to do with what is legal, IMHO.<br />
